'''Kobe Suitengū'''（こうべすいてんぐう） is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|qid=Q845945|lt=Shinto Shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} ({{ill|Suitengū|en|Suitengū|qid=Q125319456|lt=Suiten-gu|1=Suitengū}}) located in {{ill|Hyōgo Prefecture|en|Hyōgo Prefecture|qid=Q130290|lt=Hyōgo Prefecture|1=Hyōgo Prefecture}}{{ill|Kobe|en|Kobe|qid=Q48320|lt=Kobe City|1=Kobe}}{{ill|Nagata-ku, Kobe|en|Nagata-ku, Kobe|qid=Q1078801|lt=Nagata Ward|1=Nagata-ku, Kobe}}{{ill|Nagata Tenjin Town|ja|長田天神町|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nagata Tenjin Town|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}.

== Enshrined Deities ==
It enshrines {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天御中主神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amenominakanushi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 天之御中主神}} as its principal deity, and also enshrines {{ill|Emperor Antoku|en|Emperor Antoku|qid=Q316651|lt=Emperor Antoku|1=Emperor Antoku}}, {{ill|Taira no Tokuko|en|Taira no Tokuko|qid=Q3315855|lt=Kenreimonin (Heitokuji)|1=Taira no Tokuko}}, and {{ill|Taira no Tokiko|en|Taira no Tokiko|qid=Q3379244|lt=Second-Rank Nun Hira Tokushi|1=Taira no Tokiko}}.

== History ==
According to the shrine legend, on Mount Tenjin—the location of this shrine—there is a tradition that during the time of {{ill|Kojidai|ja|神代|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kojidai|1=Age of the gods (Japanese mythology)|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q3577055}}, {{ill|Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto|qid=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主神|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kotoshironushi|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 事代主|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}} descended from heaven, and the mountain was revered as a sacred mountain called Unade Hill (宇奈弖（うなで）の丘). In Taishō 3 ({{ill|1914|en|1914|qid=Q2083|lt=1914|1=1914}}), the shrine’s first {{ill|Chief Priest|ja|宮司|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Chief Priest|1=Gūji|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11453500}}, Nishigakuji, took the initiative to enshrine a branch spirit ({{ill|Bunrei|en|Bunrei|qid=Q195793|lt=Bunrei|1=Bunrei}}) from the Suiten-gu enshrined in {{ill|Fukuoka Prefecture|en|Fukuoka Prefecture|qid=Q123258|lt=Fukuoka Prefecture|1=Fukuoka Prefecture}}{{ill|Kurume|en|Kurume|qid=Q320934|lt=Kurume City|1=Kurume}} ({{ill|Kurume Suitengū|en|Kurume Suitengū|qid=Q3200625|lt=Suiten-gu|1=Kurume Suitengū}}). After an offering at Kusunoki in {{ill|Hyōgo-ku, Kobe|en|Hyōgo-ku, Kobe|qid=Q1078790|lt=Hyōgo Ward|1=Hyōgo-ku, Kobe}}, it was temporarily enshrined at Kumano Shrine in {{ill|Nagata-ku, Kobe|en|Nagata-ku, Kobe|qid=Q1078801|lt=Nagata Ward|1=Nagata-ku, Kobe}}. In Taishō 11, October, a provisional main shrine was established on Unade Hill; and in the following April of Taishō 12, the shrine was transferred to its main location and enshrined as “Kobe Suitengū.”

